\begin_inset Formula $\Answer$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In set theory, two direct corollaries of set-theoretic axioms are that every
 set contains the empty set as a subset, and every set contains itself as
 a subset.
 In other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a set, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 By extension, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \emptyset,X\right\} \subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\complement}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $X\smallsetminus X=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset^{\complement}=X\smallsetminus\emptyset=X\in\left\{ \emptyset,X\right\} $
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \emptyset,X\right\} $
\end_inset

 is closed under complements.
 Also note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset\cup X=X\in\left\{ \emptyset,X\right\} $
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \emptyset,X\right\} $
\end_inset

 only has just two elements, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \emptyset,X\right\} $
\end_inset

 must also be closed under finite and countable unions.
 So, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \emptyset,X\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 If we omit one of these elements, the set is no longer closed under complements
, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \emptyset,X\right\} $
\end_inset

 must be the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra for any 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Next, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

 must always be a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 since for any subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subseteq X$
\end_inset

, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\complement}=X\smallsetminus S\in{\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

, and for any countable set of subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ S_{i}\subseteq X\right\} _{i=1}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, we know that the union of each element 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i=1}^{\infty}S_{i}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 since an arbitrary union of subsets of a given set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is always itself a subset of that set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (and therefore is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

 by definition), since if it was not, it would contain an element that is
 not in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, which means that at least one element in one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

's would not lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

; but, that would make 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 no longer a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, so this must not be the case.
 Now that it's obvious 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we can reason that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

 is the largest of all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebras of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, since if there were one larger, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Sigma\right|>\left|{\cal P}(X)\right|$
\end_inset

, this would mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 contains as an element a set (say 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

) that does not lie in 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

, which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 would contain an element 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 that is not a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts the very definition of an algebra in 1.1—any algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a family of 
\emph on
subsets
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can now reason that any arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

, must be a superset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \emptyset,X\right\} $
\end_inset

 and a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 contains only subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by definition, so every element of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

, so that means 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}\subseteq{\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Also, since every algebra must contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 by definition, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 must be in 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 by extension, since 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 must be closed under complements.
\end_layout

