\begin_inset Formula $\Answer$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the disjoint sets 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\sm B$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subset A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A=B\cup\left(A\sm B\right)$
\end_inset

.
 From Remark 4.18 and Theorem 4.19, we know the Lebesgue integral is countably
 sub-additive for simple functions, and Lebesgue integrals can be approximated
 arbitrarily precisely by simple functions.
 The sub-additivity property gives us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\li fA=\li fB+\li f{A\sm B}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(A\sm B)=0$
\end_inset

 so we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\li fB=\li fA$
\end_inset

 for the lower bound on 
\begin_inset Formula $\li fB$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


